<font color="#FF0000">TURN THE CHEEK, BUT RELOAD</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec 28 12:42:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br><br>
Dear Pat<br>
What beautiful words you have inscribed for us to read. They certainly reflect your interest in the scriptures and your belief in what they say. They also reflect your great insight into the human character and MTF’s psychological well being.<br><br>
James the Lord’s brother writing to converted Jews, because they were more knowledgeable in religious matters then others and therefore God would require much more from them, wrote: <br><br>
“Therefore to him that knoweth to do good, and doeth it not, to him it is sin.” (James 4:17) <br><br>
Jeb proclaims to have had a real understanding of the war at that time. He stated on another post #20, Vets and None-vets a dialog, two days before the above post,<br><br>
“I actively avoided going to Vietnam, and I am not ashamed to say that. I thought the war was wrong and<br>
made a decision that I would not participate in it. I also made the decision that I would do all I could to help others not participate in it. I fought hard, and long 8 years to help stop the war.”<br><br>
Here we have an individual who is displaying his high moral superiority in understanding what the war was all about. He devoted eight years of his life, time and efforts to an anti-war effort, yet he did not, it seems to have taken the time to see the crimes and atrocities being committed in South Vietnam by invading Communist trained soldiers. He did not stand up and condemn the slaughter of innocent and unarmed South Vietnamese women and children, no, instead he tells us that he feels “NO GUILT” for what he did.<br><br>
Then he turns around and condemns us for any guilt we may have, which is by the way, unmerited guilt laid upon us by our fellow Americans. By the Anti-war protestors, professors of our educational institutions and others. <br><br>
We fought our country’s battle, saw our friends killed and wounded and when we came home we could not share those memories with our loved ones, because they had become confused about the war and our efforts there. Negative reports about the war in Vietnam were sensationalized. The six O’clock war showed them a one sided view that condemn our efforts. <br><br>
While it was the South Vietnamese Army fighting Communist North Vietnamese soldiers in Trang Bang, where Kim Phuc (the naked little girl that was burned with napalm), was photographed, as she ran from where a Vietnamese flown aircraft had accidentally dropped it. It was the American fighting men that was scorned and condemned for the act.  Forgotten was the fact that the NVA where invading the South and the South were protecting their own village. Such distortions of the truth we have had to endure with shame as Vietnam veterans. <br><br>
And so what did we get when we returned home? Silence and rejection from those we had honorably served for. We received hatred and anger and this gave raise to deeply held resentment, pain, silent suffering, confusion about what we did and why we were treated so badly for doing what was right and here you now tell us to turn the other cheek.<br><br>
Pat, you need to think of the Vietnam veteran as Job, remember that story? The problem is that the Vietnam veteran has yet to be recognized for his efforts. <br><br>
We have had to endure because of individuals that were involved in the anti-war effort who protested the war so loud and angrily that the American people lost their heart in helping others. It was American’s shame and we the Vietnam veteran remind them of their cowardice and failure to support its fighting men and because of that American lost its glory and that great shame seemes to once again fall upon us.<br><br>
Then you tell MTF to turn the other cheek, but how is it possible for us to turn from what we knew was right in our eyes. Jesus protested when smitten on the cheek &lt;John 18:22&gt;. And Jesus denounced the Pharisees &lt;Matt. 23&gt; and always fought the devil. I can tell you that the God that is coming back is not a “Happy Camper,” why don’t you tell Him to turn the other cheek?<br><br>
Righteous indignation is part of the make up of the children of God, otherwise God would not have commanded his armies to do battle against the forces of evil. I could not live with myself if I had not responded to my country’s battle cry. I saw what destructive violence the enemy reeked upon innocent civilians, first hand. Saw them as they forced little kids and old women to run along side of them during the heat of battle, so that we wouldn’t fire, then turn around and shoot the civilians themselves. <br>
 <br>
Did I kill any women or children during those times, probably, I don’t know, I shot at the enemy not the innocent bystanders. But, I can see how others forced with the same decision I was faced with may feel guilt for fighting in that type of war. <br>
I did what I could, yet when I returned home I was seen by my fellow countrymen as NOT a returning hero but as a warmonger. Why? Because of individuals involved in the anti-war movement who condemned our efforts in South East Asia, but selectively chose to remain silent about the innocent killings an atheistic nation was executing there.<br><br>
When we examine the scriptures you have mentioned (Matt 5:39, Luke 6:29) in regards to the turning of the other cheek in its content, we find that the Lord is actually laying down the ground work for what He later tells His disciples, which is get out of my way, I will re-pay. Turn the other cheek in Greek can be seen as He saying to us, you that practice what you know is right in your heart can expect to get slap over and over again and again, so be prepared for it, turn the other cheek but keep going in the direction I have pointed you. He never tells us to stop from doing that which we know is right, only not to take it personally and to seek out our own revenge. <br><br>
In fact he boldly tells us, “Dearly beloved, avenge not yourselves, but rather give place unto wrath: for it is written, Vengeance is mine; I will repay, saith the Lord. Rom 12:19. Its echoed often enough for us to understand what He means in 2 Thes 1:8, Heb 10:30, Jd 1:7. They all reveal that he will seek revenge upon individuals that have prosecuted others for their efforts in doing what is right according to His word.<br><br>

